{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"95833036-caf7-451f-9c96-f5717f5066bc","content":"\n\nRun **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs workloads at their **current versions**. It fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer packages needed by an updated SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:** SDK went up → workloads need to go up too → `dotnet workload update`.\n\nIf the build still fails afterward, try:\n```bash\ndotnet workload update --from-previous-sdk\n```\nThis carries forward workloads that were installed for the prior SDK version.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1bb830a9-db7a-4133-8b65-e69877d66971","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a knowledge question — I can answer directly without tools.","outputTokens":249},"id":"1c1a584e-17fc-45e1-b5c1-9d6d3c15e27a","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:49:32.219Z","parentId":"c4da51a6-be2c-4569-acab-2031be3c4a37"}
